./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:7:##*Please note the following IMPORTANT issues:                     *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:8:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:9:##0. REFRAIN from editing this file by hand! Some of the parame-   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:10:##   ters are not independent. Always use a calculator.            *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:11:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:12:##1. alpha_S(MZ) has been used in the calculation of the parameters*
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:13:##   This value is KEPT by madgraph when no pdf are used lpp(i)=0, *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:14:##   but, for consistency, it will be reset by madgraph to the     *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:15:##   value expected IF the pdfs for collisions with hadrons are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:16:##   used.                                                         *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:17:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:18:##2. Values of the charm and bottom kinematic (pole) masses are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:19:##   those used in the matrix elements and phase space UNLESS they *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:20:##   are set to ZERO from the start in the model (particles.dat)   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:21:##   This happens, for example,  when using 5-flavor QCD where     *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:22:##   charm and bottom are treated as partons in the initial state  *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:23:##   and a zero mass might be hardwired in the model definition.   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:24:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:25:##       The SUSY decays have calculated using SDECAY 1.1a         *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test2.dat:26:##                                                                 *

./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:2:#                        MadGraph/MadEvent                           *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:3:#                   http://madgraph.hep.uiuc.edu                     *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:4:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:5:#                          proc_card.dat                             *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:6:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:7:# This file is used to generate the code for a specific process.     *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:8:# Some notation/conventions:                                         *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:9:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:10:# 0. Do not modify the TAGS and their order.                         *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:11:# 1. hash/pound is a comment.                                        *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:12:# 2. The number after the @ is used as an identifier for the class   *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:13:#    of processes. It can be any positive integer.                   *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:14:# 3. The number of lines for the max couplings depends on how many   *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:15:#    different classes of couplings are present in the model         *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:16:#    In the SM these are just two: QED (which include EW) and QCD    *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:17:# 4. Write "end_coup" after  the couplings list,                     *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:18:#    to tell MG that the couplings input is over.                    *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:19:# 5. Write "done" after the proc list to                             *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:20:#    to tell MG that the proc input is over.                         *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:21:# 6. Some model names available at present are:                      *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:22:#    sm     =  Standard Model                                        *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:23:#    smckm =  Standard Model with Cabibbo matrix                     *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:24:#    mssm   =  Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model                 *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:25:#    2hdm   =  Generic Two Higgs Doublet model                       *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:26:#    heft   =  Higgs EFT (+Standard Model)                           *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:27:#    usrmod =  User Model                                            *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:28:# 7. Don't leave spaces between the particles name in the            *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:29:#    definition of the multiparticles.                               *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:30:#*********************************************************************
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:31:#*********************************************************************
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:32:# Process(es) requested : mg2 input                                  *
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:33:#*********************************************************************
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:34:# Begin PROCESS # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:35:#
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:37:pp>ve~e-  @1       # First Process
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:38:QCD=99             # Max QCD couplings
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:39:QED=2              # Max QED couplings
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:40:end_coup           # End the couplings input
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:42:pp>(Z>W+(W->mu-vm)) @2       # Second Process
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:43:QCD=2             # Max QCD couplings
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:44:QED=4              # Max QED couplings
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:45:end_coup           # End the couplings input
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:47:pp>tt~ $a    @3       # Third Process
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:48:QCD=99             # Max QCD couplings
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:49:end_coup           # End the couplings input
./tests/input_files/v4_proc_card.dat:51:pp>tt~ /a $g @2           # Third Process

./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:15:##   value expected IF the pdfs for collisions with hadrons are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:16:##   used.                                                         *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:17:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:18:##2. Values of the charm and bottom kinematic (pole) masses are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:19:##   those used in the matrix elements and phase space UNLESS they *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:20:##   are set to ZERO from the start in the model (particles.dat)   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_test1.dat:21:##   This happens, for example,  when using 5-flavor QCD where     *

./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:2:#                        MadGraph/MadEvent                           *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:3:#                   http://madgraph.hep.uiuc.edu                     *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:4:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:5:#                          proc_card.dat                             *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:6:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:7:# This file is used to generate the code for a specific process.     *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:8:# Some notation/conventions:                                         *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:9:#                                                                    *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:10:# 0. Do not modify the TAGS and their order.                         *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:11:# 1. hash/pound is a comment.                                        *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:12:# 2. The number after the @ is used as an identifier for the class   *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:13:#    of processes. It can be any positive integer.                   *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:14:# 3. The number of lines for the max couplings depends on how many   *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:15:#    different classes of couplings are present in the model         *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:16:#    In the SM these are just two: QED (which include EW) and QCD    *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:17:# 4. Write "end_coup" after  the couplings list,                     *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:18:#    to tell MG that the couplings input is over.                    *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:19:# 5. Write "done" after the proc list to                             *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:20:#    to tell MG that the proc input is over.                         *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:21:# 6. Some model names available at present are:                      *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:22:#    sm     =  Standard Model                                        *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:23:#    smckm =  Standard Model with Cabibbo matrix                     *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:24:#    mssm   =  Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model                 *

./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:27:#    usrmod =  User Model                                            *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:28:# 7. Don't leave spaces between the particles name in the            *
./tests/input_files/simple_v4_proc_card.dat:29:#    definition of the multiparticles.                               *

./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:9:##0. REFRAIN from editing this file by hand! Some of the parame-   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:10:##   ters are not independent. Always use a calculator.            *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:11:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:12:##1. alpha_S(MZ) has been used in the calculation of the parameters*
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:13:##   This value is KEPT by madgraph when no pdf are used lpp(i)=0, *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:14:##   but, for consistency, it will be reset by madgraph to the     *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:15:##   value expected IF the pdfs for collisions with hadrons are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:16:##   used.                                                         *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:17:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:18:##2. Values of the charm and bottom kinematic (pole) masses are    *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:19:##   those used in the matrix elements and phase space UNLESS they *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:20:##   are set to ZERO from the start in the model (particles.dat)   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:21:##   This happens, for example,  when using 5-flavor QCD where     *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:22:##   charm and bottom are treated as partons in the initial state  *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:23:##   and a zero mass might be hardwired in the model definition.   *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:24:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/param_card_0.dat:25:##       The SUSY decays have calculated using SDECAY 1.1a         *

./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:4:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:5:##  param_card corresponding the SPS point 1a (by SoftSusy 2.0.5)  *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:6:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:7:##******************************************************************
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:8:## Les Houches friendly file for the (MS)SM parameters of MadGraph *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:9:##      SM parameter set and decay widths produced by MSSMCalc     *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:10:##******************************************************************
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:11:##*Please note the following IMPORTANT issues:                     *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:12:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:13:##0. REFRAIN from editing this file by hand! Some of the parame-   *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:14:##   ters are not independent. Always use a calculator.            *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:15:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:16:##1. alpha_S(MZ) has been used in the calculation of the parameters*
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:17:##   This value is KEPT by madgraph when no pdf are used lpp(i)=0, *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:18:##   but, for consistency, it will be reset by madgraph to the     *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:19:##   value expected IF the pdfs for collisions with hadrons are    *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:20:##   used.                                                         *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:21:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:22:##2. Values of the charm and bottom kinematic (pole) masses are    *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:23:##   those used in the matrix elements and phase space UNLESS they *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:24:##   are set to ZERO from the start in the model (particles.dat)   *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:25:##   This happens, for example,  when using 5-flavor QCD where     *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:26:##   charm and bottom are treated as partons in the initial state  *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:27:##   and a zero mass might be hardwired in the model definition.   *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:28:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:29:##       The SUSY decays have calculated using SDECAY 1.1a         *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:30:##                                                                 *
./tests/input_files/sps1a_param_card.dat:31:##******************************************************************

./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:74:# Decay channels                                                       *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:75:#***********************************************************************
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:76:# Syntax for HERWIG6                                                   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:77:# DM_I = M > D1 D2 @ BR @ ME                                           *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:78:# corresponding to call to HWMODK(M,BR,ME,D1,D2)                       *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:79:# I < 100, M is the decaying resonance, D1, D2, ... are the decay      *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:80:# products (up to five), BR is the branching ratio and ME is the type  *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:81:# of matrix element to be used in the decay.                           *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:82:# BR's are correctly understood only if they add up to 1, and only if  *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:83:# no more than three modes are required for a given resonance.         *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:84:# WARNING: the order of decay products in > 2-body decays IS RELEVANT. *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:85:#                                                                      *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:86:# Syntax for PYTHIA6                                                   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:87:# DM_I = M > D1 D2 @ BR @ ME                                           *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:88:# WARNING: turning hadronisation off disables top decays               *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:89:# WARNING: 1 -> n decays (with n > 2) are handled through a sequence   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:90:# of 1 -> 2 decays.                                                    *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:91:# WARNING: entries BR and ME are ignored                               *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:92:#                                                                      *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:93:# Syntax for HERWIG++                                                  *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:94:# DM_I = M > D1 D2 @ BR @ ME                                           *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:95:# WARNING: entries BR and ME are ignored                               *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:96:#                                                                      *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:97:# Syntax for PYTHIA8                                                   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:98:# DM_I = M:onIfAny = D1 D2                                             *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:99:# or similar, according to the offical PYTHIA8 decay syntax, see       *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:100:# the online PYTHIA8 manual                                            *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:101:# WARNING: 1 -> n decays (with n > 2) are handled through a sequence   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:102:# of 1 -> 2 decays.                                                    *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:103:#                                                                      *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:104:# Examples                                                             *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:105:# Z -> e+ e- or mu+ mu- with BR = 0.5 each, HERWIG6                    *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:106:# DM_1 = 23 > -11 11 @ 0.5d0 @ 100
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:107:# DM_2 = 23 > -13 13 @ 0.5d0 @ 100
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:108:# H -> ta+ ta- with BR = 1, HERWIG6 or HERWIG++                        *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:109:# DM_3 = 25 > -15 15 @ 1.0d0 @ 0
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:110:# t -> ve e+ b with BR = 1, HERWIG6 or HERWIG++                        *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:111:# DM_4 = 6 > 12 -11 5 @ 1d0 @ 100
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:112:# t -> ve e+ b with BR = 1, PYTHIA6                                    *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:113:# DM_5 = 6 > 24 5 @ 1d0 @ 100
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:114:# DM_6 = 24 > 12 -11 @ 1d0 @ 100
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:115:# W+ -> ve e+, W- -> vm~ mu-, PYTHIA8                                  *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:116:# DM_1 = 24:onMode = off
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:117:# DM_2 = 24:onPosIfAny = 11 12
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:118:# DM_3 = 24:onNegIfAny = 13 14
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:119:# W+ -> ve e+, W- -> ve~ e- and vm~ mu-, PYTHIA8                       *
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:120:# DM_1 = 24:onMode = off
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:121:# DM_2 = 24:onIfAny = 11 12
./Template/NLO/Cards/shower_card.dat:122:# DM_3 = 24:onNegIfAny = 13 14

./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:13:# Can either be 'topdrawer', 'root', 'HwU', 'LHE' or 'none'.
./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:14:# When choosing HwU, it comes with a GnuPlot wrapper. When choosing
./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:15:# topdrawer, the histogramming package 'dbook.f' is included in the
./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:16:# code, while when choosing root the 'rbook_fe8.f' and 'rbook_be8.cc'
./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:17:# are included. If 'none' is chosen, all the other entries below have
./Template/NLO/Cards/FO_analyse_card.dat:18:# to be set empty.

./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:151:# Cuts on the jets. Jet clustering is performed by FastJet.            *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:152:#  - If gamma_is_j, photons are also clustered with jets.              *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:153:#    Otherwise, they will be treated as tagged particles and photon    * 
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:154:#    isolation will be applied. Note that photons in the real emission *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:155:#    will always be clustered with QCD partons.                        *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:156:#  - When matching to a parton shower, these generation cuts should be *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:157:#    considerably softer than the analysis cuts.                       *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:158:#  - More specific cuts can be specified in SubProcesses/cuts.f        *

./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:210:# Folding parameters for S-events to reduce the number of negatively   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:211:# weighted events. Allowed values are 1, 2, 4 or 8 for each of the     *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:212:# three variables. Typically, folding in xi_i or y_ij results in the   *
./Template/NLO/Cards/run_card.dat:213:# largest reduction of negatively weighted events. (arXiv:2002.12716)  *

./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:1:#**************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:2:#                      Card for MadAnalysis                               *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:3:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:4:# This file is used to set the classes and options for                    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:5:# the MadAnalysis program.                                                *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:6:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:7:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:8:# Some comments about the classes                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:9:# 1. Plots are for classes of particles.                                  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:10:# 2. Each particle is identified by its PDG code.                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:11:# 3. Classes names are arbitrary (4 symbols max, no spaces allowed).      *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:12:# 4. Particles in the same class will be ordered with the 'ordering       *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:13:#    function' in the file in_func.f.                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:14:# 5. Classes can be added/edited/removed at will, and given a name        *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:15:#    that will then appear in the plots.                                  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:16:# 6. A particle can be put in one class only. Putting a particle in       *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:17:#    two or more classes can lead to double counting of events.           *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:18:# 7. The class name mET is missing Energy and its name is reserved.       *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:19:#    If used, it must be put last in the classes list below.              *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:20:# 8. If events contain particles not belonging to an existing class,      *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:21:#    a new class will automatically be generated.                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:22:# 9. For LHCO events the PDG code 21 is assigned to a jet (not            *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:23:#    b-tagged), 5 to a b-tagged jet and 12 to missing ET.                 *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:24:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:25:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:26:# Some comments about the cuts                                            *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:27:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions on which cuts can be applied    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:28:#    are given.                                                           *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:29:# 2. The syntax is as follows.                                            *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:30:#      etmin 1 3 30d0                                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:31:#     means that from the first class the Et of the first three particles *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:32:#     has to be greater than 30 GeV.                                      *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:33:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:34:#      etmissmin 20d0                                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:35:#     means that there must be at least 20 GeV of missing Et              *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:36:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:37:#      dRmin 2 1 4 3 3d0                                                  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:38:#     means that the distance between the first particle in the second    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:39:#     class and the first three particles in the fourth class has to be   *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:40:#     greater than 3.                                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:41:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:42:#      ptmax 1 3 10d0                                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:43:#      ptmax 1 2 15d0                                                     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:44:#     means that the maximum pt of the third particle in the first class  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:45:#     has to smaller than 10 GeV, and the first two particles of this     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:46:#     class has to be smaller than 15 GeV                                 *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:47:# 3. The ordering of the particles within a class can be set with the     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:48:#    'ordering function' in the file kin_func.f.                          *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:49:# 4. For all the 'min' cuts, an event will be thrown away if the particle *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:50:#    does not exist. On the other hand, for all the 'max' cuts the cut    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:51:#    will be ignored if the particle does not exist                       *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:52:#    (Only dRij is an exception, for which it is the other way around)    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:53:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:54:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:55:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:56:# Some comments about the plotting options                                *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:57:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions can be found that can be        *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:58:#    plotted. (only for off-line usage)                                   *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:59:# 2. With the plotting options one can set the number of plots for each   *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:60:#    of these functions.                                                  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:61:# 3. One has to specify for each variable which particles from which      *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:62:#    class are used to set the plots. Syntax:                             *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:63:#    	et  2 4                                                           *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:64:#    means that the transverse energy of the first four particles in the  *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:65:#    second class will be plotted.                                        *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:66:#       mij 1 3                                                           *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:67:#	mij 2 2                                                           *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:68:#    means that for the invariant mass plots the first three particles    *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:69:#    from the first class and the first two from the second class will be *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:70:#    used to plot the invariant mass of two particles. (10 plots)         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:71:# 4. The ordering of the particles in a class can be set with the         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:72:#    'ordering_function'. pt, e and et are valid functions. (For off-line *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:73:#    users X1, X2 and X3 can also be used, if defined in kin_func.f.)     *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:74:# 5. Max number of plots is 200.                                          *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:75:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:76:#                                                                         *
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:77:#**************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:78:# Put here your list of classes
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:79:#**************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:80:# Do NOT put spaces before class names!
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:81:# Begin Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:82:jet  1 -1 2 -2 3 -3 4 -4 21   # Class number 1
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:83:b    5 -5                     # Class number 2
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:84:mET  12 -12 14 -14 16 -16 1000022    # Missing ET class, name is reserved
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:85:# End Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:86:#**************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:87:ordering_function pt  # orders particles in classes according to their pt
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:88:normalization xsec    # histogram normalization, xsec or number (e.g. 1)
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:89:#**************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:90:# Put here list of minimum pt for the classes
./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:91:#**************************************************************************

./Template/Common/Cards/plot_card.dat:96:# End Minpts # This is TAG. Do not modify this line

./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:1:#*************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:2:#                          Reweight Module                               *
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:3:#                Matrix-Element reweighting at LO/NLO                    *
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:4:#  Mattelaer Olivier                                    arxiv:1607.00763 *  
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:5:#*************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:6:#          
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:7:# Note: 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:8:#   1) the value of alpha_s will be used from the event so the value in
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:9:#      the param_card is not taken into account.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:10:#   2) It is (in general) dangerous/wrong to change parameters by a large
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:11:#      amount, if this changes the shape of the matrix elements a lot.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:12:#      (For example, changing a particle's mass by much more than its
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:13:#      width leads to very inaccurate result). In such a case, separate 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:14:#      event generation runs are needed.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:15:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:16:#************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:17:# ENTER YOUR COMMANDS BELOW. 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:18:#************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:20:change mode NLO    # Define type of Reweighting. For LO sample this command
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:21:                   # has no effect since only "LO" mode is allowed.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:23:#uncomment if you do not want to overwrite the reweight file of Sudakov in rw_me
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:24:#change rwgt_dir /PATH_MG5_BRANCH/NAME_FOLDER
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:26:#uncomment if you want to use Sudakov Reweight
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:27:#change include_sudakov True
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:32:#  SPECIFY A PATH OR USE THE SET COMMAND LIKE THIS:
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:33:# set sminputs 1 130 # modify 1/alpha_EW
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:37:#************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:38:# Manual:      https://cp3.irmp.ucl.ac.be/projects/madgraph/wiki/Reweight
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:39:#************************************************************************
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:40:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:41:# Example of (standard) code for the computation of two weights:
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:42:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:43:# launch                    ! tag to start the computation of the first weight
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:44:#  set BLOCKNAME ID VALUE   ! rule to modify the current param_card
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:45:#  set BLOCKNAME ID VALUE   ! rule to modify the current param_card
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:46:# launch                    ! start to compute a second weight
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:47:#  /home/Cards/param_card_2.dat ! you can also enter a path to a valid card
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:48:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:49:# Note: The command to specify the parameter are AFTER the associated "launch" 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:50:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:51:# Possible options: 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:52:#   You can enter one of the following lines to customize the reweighting 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:53:#   procedure. These need to be given before the 'launch' command.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:54:#
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:55:# change model NAME : use another model for the matrix-elements to reweight 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:56:#        with. In this case you need to provide the path to a correct 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:57:#        param_card for the new model; you cannot modify the original one 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:58:#        with the 'set' command.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:59:# change process DEF [--add]: change the process by which you reweight. 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:60:#        The initial and final state particles of the new process should 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:61:#        be exactly identical to the ones in the original process.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:62:# change helicity False: perform the reweighting by helicity summed 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:63:#        matrix-elements even if the events have been written with a 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:64:#        single helicity state.       
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:65:# change mode XXX: change the type of reweighting performed.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:66:#        allowed values: LO, NLO, LO+NLO
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:67:#        - This command has no effect for reweighting an .lhe event file with LO accuracy. 
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:68:#          In that case LO mode is always used (whatever entry is set).
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:69:#        - When the .lhe file reweighted is at NLO accuracy, then all modes are allowed.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:70:#          * "LO" is an approximate leading order method
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:71:#          * "NLO" is the NLO accurate method
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:72:#          * "LO+NLO" runs both
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:73:#       - "NLO" and "LO+NLO" modes requires 'store_rwgt_info' equals True (run_card.dat)
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:74:#          If the reweighting is done at generation level this parameter will
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:75:#          automatically be set on True.
./Template/Common/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:76:#************************************************************************

./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:7:# Please note the following IMPORTANT issues:                      *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:8:#                                                                   *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:9:# 0. REFRAIN from editing this file by hand! Some of the parame-    *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:10:#    ters are not independent                                       *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:11:#    (such as G_Fermi, alpha_em, sin(theta_W),MZ,MW) and serious    *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:12:#    problems might be encountered (such as violation of unitarity  *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:13:#    or gauge invariance).  Always use a calculator.                *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:14:#                                                                   *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:15:# 1. alpha_S(MZ) has been used in the calculation of the parameters *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:16:#    but, for consistency, it will be reset by MadGraph5_aMC@NLO to *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:17:#    the value expected IF the pdfs for collisions with hadrons are *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:18:#    used. This value is KEPT by MadGraph5_aMC@NLO when no pdf are  *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:19:#    usedlpp(i)=0 .                                                 *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:20:#                                                                   *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:21:# 2. Values of the charm and bottom kinematic (pole) masses are     *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:22:#    those used in the matrix elements and phase space UNLESS they  *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:23:#    are set to ZERO from the start in the model (particles.dat)    *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:24:#    This happens, for example,  when using 5-flavor QCD where      *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:25:#    charm and bottom are treated as partons in the initial state   *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:26:#    and a zero mass might be hardwired in the model definition.    *
./Template/LO/Cards/param_card_default.dat:27:#                                                                   *

./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:1:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:2:#                      Card for MadAnalysis                               *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:3:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:4:# This file is used to set the classes and options for                    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:5:# the MadAnalysis program.                                                *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:6:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:7:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:8:# Some comments about the classes                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:9:# 1. Plots are for classes of particles.                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:10:# 2. Each particle is identified by its PDG code.                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:11:# 3. Classes names are arbitrary (4 symbols max, no spaces allowed).      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:12:# 4. Particles in the same class will be ordered with the 'ordering       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:13:#    function' in the file in_func.f.                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:14:# 5. Classes can be added/edited/removed at will, and given a name        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:15:#    that will then appear in the plots.                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:16:# 6. A particle can be put in one class only. Putting a particle in       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:17:#    two or more classes can lead to double counting of events.           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:18:# 7. The class name mET is missing Energy and its name is reserved.       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:19:#    If used, it must be put last in the classes list below.              *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:20:# 8. If events contain particles not belonging to an existing class,      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:21:#    a new class will automatically be generated.                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:22:# 9. For LHCO events the PDG code 21 is assigned to a jet (not            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:23:#    b-tagged), 5 to a b-tagged jet and 12 to missing ET.                 *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:24:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:25:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:26:# Some comments about the cuts                                            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:27:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions on which cuts can be applied    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:28:#    are given.                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:29:# 2. The syntax is as follows.                                            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:30:#      etmin 1 3 30d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:31:#     means that from the first class the Et of the first three particles *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:32:#     has to be greater than 30 GeV.                                      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:33:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:34:#      etmissmin 20d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:35:#     means that there must be at least 20 GeV of missing Et              *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:36:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:37:#      dRmin 2 1 4 3 3d0                                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:38:#     means that the distance between the first particle in the second    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:39:#     class and the first three particles in the fourth class has to be   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:40:#     greater than 3.                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:41:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:42:#      ptmax 1 3 10d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:43:#      ptmax 1 2 15d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:44:#     means that the maximum pt of the third particle in the first class  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:45:#     has to smaller than 10 GeV, and the first two particles of this     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:46:#     class has to be smaller than 15 GeV                                 *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:47:# 3. The ordering of the particles within a class can be set with the     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:48:#    'ordering function' in the file kin_func.f.                          *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:49:# 4. For all the 'min' cuts, an event will be thrown away if the particle *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:50:#    does not exist. On the other hand, for all the 'max' cuts the cut    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:51:#    will be ignored if the particle does not exist                       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:52:#    (Only dRij is an exception, for which it is the other way around)    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:53:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:54:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:55:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:56:# Some comments about the plotting options                                *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:57:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions can be found that can be        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:58:#    plotted. (only for off-line usage)                                   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:59:# 2. With the plotting options one can set the number of plots for each   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:60:#    of these functions.                                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:61:# 3. One has to specify for each variable which particles from which      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:62:#    class are used to set the plots. Syntax:                             *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:63:#    	et  2 4                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:64:#    means that the transverse energy of the first four particles in the  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:65:#    second class will be plotted.                                        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:66:#       mij 1 3                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:67:#	mij 2 2                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:68:#    means that for the invariant mass plots the first three particles    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:69:#    from the first class and the first two from the second class will be *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:70:#    used to plot the invariant mass of two particles. (10 plots)         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:71:# 4. The ordering of the particles in a class can be set with the         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:72:#    'ordering_function'. pt, e and et are valid functions. (For off-line *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:73:#    users X1, X2 and X3 can also be used, if defined in kin_func.f.)     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:74:# 5. Max number of plots is 200.                                          *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:75:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:76:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:77:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/.plot_card.dat:78:# Put here your list of classes

./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:1:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:2:#                      Card for MadAnalysis                               *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:3:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:4:# This file is used to set the classes and options for                    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:5:# the MadAnalysis program.                                                *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:6:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:7:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:8:# Some comments about the classes                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:9:# 1. Plots are for classes of particles.                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:10:# 2. Each particle is identified by its PDG code.                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:11:# 3. Classes names are arbitrary (4 symbols max, no spaces allowed).      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:12:# 4. Particles in the same class will be ordered with the 'ordering       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:13:#    function' in the file in_func.f.                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:14:# 5. Classes can be added/edited/removed at will, and given a name        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:15:#    that will then appear in the plots.                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:16:# 6. A particle can be put in one class only. Putting a particle in       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:17:#    two or more classes can lead to double counting of events.           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:18:# 7. The class name mET is missing Energy and its name is reserved.       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:19:#    If used, it must be put last in the classes list below.              *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:20:# 8. If events contain particles not belonging to an existing class,      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:21:#    a new class will automatically be generated.                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:22:# 9. For LHCO events the PDG code 21 is assigned to a jet (not            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:23:#    b-tagged), 5 to a b-tagged jet and 12 to missing ET.                 *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:24:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:25:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:26:# Some comments about the cuts                                            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:27:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions on which cuts can be applied    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:28:#    are given.                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:29:# 2. The syntax is as follows.                                            *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:30:#      etmin 1 3 30d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:31:#     means that from the first class the Et of the first three particles *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:32:#     has to be greater than 30 GeV.                                      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:33:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:34:#      etmissmin 20d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:35:#     means that there must be at least 20 GeV of missing Et              *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:36:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:37:#      dRmin 2 1 4 3 3d0                                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:38:#     means that the distance between the first particle in the second    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:39:#     class and the first three particles in the fourth class has to be   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:40:#     greater than 3.                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:41:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:42:#      ptmax 1 3 10d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:43:#      ptmax 1 2 15d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:44:#     means that the maximum pt of the third particle in the first class  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:45:#     has to smaller than 10 GeV, and the first two particles of this     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:46:#     class has to be smaller than 15 GeV                                 *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:47:# 3. The ordering of the particles within a class can be set with the     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:48:#    'ordering function' in the file kin_func.f.                          *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:49:# 4. For all the 'min' cuts, an event will be thrown away if the particle *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:50:#    does not exist. On the other hand, for all the 'max' cuts the cut    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:51:#    will be ignored if the particle does not exist                       *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:52:#    (Only dRij is an exception, for which it is the other way around)    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:53:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:54:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:55:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:56:# Some comments about the plotting options                                *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:57:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions can be found that can be        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:58:#    plotted. (only for off-line usage)                                   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:59:# 2. With the plotting options one can set the number of plots for each   *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:60:#    of these functions.                                                  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:61:# 3. One has to specify for each variable which particles from which      *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:62:#    class are used to set the plots. Syntax:                             *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:63:#    	et  2 4                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:64:#    means that the transverse energy of the first four particles in the  *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:65:#    second class will be plotted.                                        *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:66:#       mij 1 3                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:67:#	mij 2 2                                                           *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:68:#    means that for the invariant mass plots the first three particles    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:69:#    from the first class and the first two from the second class will be *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:70:#    used to plot the invariant mass of two particles. (10 plots)         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:71:# 4. The ordering of the particles in a class can be set with the         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:72:#    'ordering_function'. pt, e and et are valid functions. (For off-line *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:73:#    users X1, X2 and X3 can also be used, if defined in kin_func.f.)     *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:74:# 5. Max number of plots is 200.                                          *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:75:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:76:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:77:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:78:# Put here your list of classes
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:79:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:80:# Do NOT put spaces before class names!
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:81:# Begin Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:82:jet  1 -1 2 -2 3 -3 4 -4 21   # Class number 1
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:83:b    5 -5                     # Class number 2
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:84:mET  12 -12 14 -14 16 -16 1000022    # Missing ET class, name is reserved
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:85:# End Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:86:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:87:ordering_function pt  # orders particles in classes according to their pt
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/plot_card_default.dat:88:normalization xsec    # histogram normalization, xsec or number (e.g. 1)

./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:1:#*************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:2:#                          Reweight Module                               *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:3:#                Matrix-Element reweighting at LO/NLO                    *
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:4:#  Mattelaer Olivier                                    arxiv:1607.00763 *  
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:5:#*************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:6:#          
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:7:# Note: 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:8:#   1) the value of alpha_s will be used from the event so the value in
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:9:#      the param_card is not taken into account.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:10:#   2) It is (in general) dangerous/wrong to change parameters by a large
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:11:#      amount, if this changes the shape of the matrix elements a lot.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:12:#      (For example, changing a particle's mass by much more than its
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:13:#      width leads to very inaccurate result). In such a case, separate 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:14:#      event generation runs are needed.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:15:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:16:#************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:17:# ENTER YOUR COMMANDS BELOW. 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:18:#************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:20:change mode NLO    # Define type of Reweighting. For LO sample this command
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:21:                   # has no effect since only "LO" mode is allowed.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:23:#uncomment if you do not want to overwrite the reweight file of Sudakov in rw_me
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:24:#change rwgt_dir /PATH_MG5_BRANCH/NAME_FOLDER
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:26:#uncomment if you want to use Sudakov Reweight
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:27:#change include_sudakov True
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:32:#  SPECIFY A PATH OR USE THE SET COMMAND LIKE THIS:
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:33:# set sminputs 1 130 # modify 1/alpha_EW
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:37:#************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:38:# Manual:      https://cp3.irmp.ucl.ac.be/projects/madgraph/wiki/Reweight
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:39:#************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:40:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:41:# Example of (standard) code for the computation of two weights:
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:42:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:43:# launch                    ! tag to start the computation of the first weight
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:44:#  set BLOCKNAME ID VALUE   ! rule to modify the current param_card
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:45:#  set BLOCKNAME ID VALUE   ! rule to modify the current param_card
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:46:# launch                    ! start to compute a second weight
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:47:#  /home/Cards/param_card_2.dat ! you can also enter a path to a valid card
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:48:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:49:# Note: The command to specify the parameter are AFTER the associated "launch" 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:50:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:51:# Possible options: 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:52:#   You can enter one of the following lines to customize the reweighting 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:53:#   procedure. These need to be given before the 'launch' command.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:54:#
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:55:# change model NAME : use another model for the matrix-elements to reweight 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:56:#        with. In this case you need to provide the path to a correct 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:57:#        param_card for the new model; you cannot modify the original one 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:58:#        with the 'set' command.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:59:# change process DEF [--add]: change the process by which you reweight. 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:60:#        The initial and final state particles of the new process should 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:61:#        be exactly identical to the ones in the original process.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:62:# change helicity False: perform the reweighting by helicity summed 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:63:#        matrix-elements even if the events have been written with a 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:64:#        single helicity state.       
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:65:# change mode XXX: change the type of reweighting performed.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:66:#        allowed values: LO, NLO, LO+NLO
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:67:#        - This command has no effect for reweighting an .lhe event file with LO accuracy. 
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:68:#          In that case LO mode is always used (whatever entry is set).
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:69:#        - When the .lhe file reweighted is at NLO accuracy, then all modes are allowed.
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:70:#          * "LO" is an approximate leading order method
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:71:#          * "NLO" is the NLO accurate method
./PROC_sm_1/Cards/reweight_card_default.dat:72:#          * "LO+NLO" runs both

./PROC_sm_0/Cards/madanalysis5_parton_card_default.dat:1:# This card is used only if MA5 failed to create a default for this run

./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:1:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:2:#                      Card for MadAnalysis                               *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:3:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:4:# This file is used to set the classes and options for                    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:5:# the MadAnalysis program.                                                *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:6:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:7:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:8:# Some comments about the classes                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:9:# 1. Plots are for classes of particles.                                  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:10:# 2. Each particle is identified by its PDG code.                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:11:# 3. Classes names are arbitrary (4 symbols max, no spaces allowed).      *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:12:# 4. Particles in the same class will be ordered with the 'ordering       *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:13:#    function' in the file in_func.f.                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:14:# 5. Classes can be added/edited/removed at will, and given a name        *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:15:#    that will then appear in the plots.                                  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:16:# 6. A particle can be put in one class only. Putting a particle in       *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:17:#    two or more classes can lead to double counting of events.           *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:18:# 7. The class name mET is missing Energy and its name is reserved.       *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:19:#    If used, it must be put last in the classes list below.              *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:20:# 8. If events contain particles not belonging to an existing class,      *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:21:#    a new class will automatically be generated.                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:22:# 9. For LHCO events the PDG code 21 is assigned to a jet (not            *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:23:#    b-tagged), 5 to a b-tagged jet and 12 to missing ET.                 *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:24:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:25:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:26:# Some comments about the cuts                                            *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:27:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions on which cuts can be applied    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:28:#    are given.                                                           *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:29:# 2. The syntax is as follows.                                            *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:30:#      etmin 1 3 30d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:31:#     means that from the first class the Et of the first three particles *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:32:#     has to be greater than 30 GeV.                                      *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:33:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:34:#      etmissmin 20d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:35:#     means that there must be at least 20 GeV of missing Et              *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:36:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:37:#      dRmin 2 1 4 3 3d0                                                  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:38:#     means that the distance between the first particle in the second    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:39:#     class and the first three particles in the fourth class has to be   *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:40:#     greater than 3.                                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:41:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:42:#      ptmax 1 3 10d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:43:#      ptmax 1 2 15d0                                                     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:44:#     means that the maximum pt of the third particle in the first class  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:45:#     has to smaller than 10 GeV, and the first two particles of this     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:46:#     class has to be smaller than 15 GeV                                 *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:47:# 3. The ordering of the particles within a class can be set with the     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:48:#    'ordering function' in the file kin_func.f.                          *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:49:# 4. For all the 'min' cuts, an event will be thrown away if the particle *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:50:#    does not exist. On the other hand, for all the 'max' cuts the cut    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:51:#    will be ignored if the particle does not exist                       *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:52:#    (Only dRij is an exception, for which it is the other way around)    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:53:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:54:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:55:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:56:# Some comments about the plotting options                                *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:57:# 1. In the file kin_func.f the functions can be found that can be        *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:58:#    plotted. (only for off-line usage)                                   *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:59:# 2. With the plotting options one can set the number of plots for each   *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:60:#    of these functions.                                                  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:61:# 3. One has to specify for each variable which particles from which      *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:62:#    class are used to set the plots. Syntax:                             *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:63:#    	et  2 4                                                           *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:64:#    means that the transverse energy of the first four particles in the  *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:65:#    second class will be plotted.                                        *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:66:#       mij 1 3                                                           *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:67:#	mij 2 2                                                           *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:68:#    means that for the invariant mass plots the first three particles    *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:69:#    from the first class and the first two from the second class will be *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:70:#    used to plot the invariant mass of two particles. (10 plots)         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:71:# 4. The ordering of the particles in a class can be set with the         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:72:#    'ordering_function'. pt, e and et are valid functions. (For off-line *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:73:#    users X1, X2 and X3 can also be used, if defined in kin_func.f.)     *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:74:# 5. Max number of plots is 200.                                          *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:75:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:76:#                                                                         *
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:77:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:78:# Put here your list of classes
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:79:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:80:# Do NOT put spaces before class names!
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:81:# Begin Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:82:jet  1 -1 2 -2 3 -3 4 -4 21   # Class number 1
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:83:b    5 -5                     # Class number 2
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:84:mET  12 -12 14 -14 16 -16 1000022    # Missing ET class, name is reserved
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:85:# End Classes # This is TAG. Do not modify this line
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:86:#**************************************************************************
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:87:ordering_function pt  # orders particles in classes according to their pt
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:88:normalization xsec    # histogram normalization, xsec or number (e.g. 1)
./PROC_sm_0/Cards/.plot_card.dat:89:#**************************************************************************

./PROC_sm_0/Cards/madanalysis5_hadron_card_default.dat:1:# This card is used only if MA5 failed to create a default for this run
